\begin_layout Remark
For any random process, we have that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lim_{t\rightarrow0}P_{2}\left(y_{2},t|y_{1}\right) & = & \delta\left(y_{2}-y_{1}\right),\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the conditional probability defined from 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "def:prob random process"

\end_inset

).*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
to see why, note that for a test function 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\int dy_{2}f\left(y_{2}\right)P_{2}\left(y_{2},t|y_{1}\right) & = & \lim_{t\rightarrow0}\int dy_{2}f\left(y_{2}\right)\frac{p_{2}\left(y_{2},t;y_{1}\right)}{p_{1}\left(y_{1}\right)}\\
 & = & \frac{1}{p_{1}\left(y_{1}\right)}\lim_{t\rightarrow0}\int dy_{2}f\left(y_{2}\right)p_{2}\left(y_{2},t;y_{1}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{1}{p_{1}\left(y_{1}\right)}\int dy_{2}f\left(y_{2}\right)p_{2}\left(y_{2},y_{1}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{1}{p_{1}\left(y_{1}\right)}\int dy_{2}f\left(y_{2}\right)p_{1}\left(y_{1}\right)\delta\left(y_{2}-y_{2}\right)\\
 & = & f\left(y_{1}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

We obtain the fourth equality from the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "def:prob random process"

\end_inset

) 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Exercise 6.1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "blandfordCP"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Stationary random processes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Preview

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}[Stationary Random Processes]
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def: Stationary Random Process"

\end_inset

A random process is said to be stationary if and only if its probability
 distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset

 depend only on time differences, not on absolute time: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n}+\tau;...;y_{2},t_{2}+\tau;y_{1},t_{1}+\tau\right) & = & p_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n};...;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1},t_{1}\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Preview

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}[Probability for Random Processes]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:prob random process"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n};...;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1},t_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 tells us the probability that the random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 will take on a value between 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}+dy_{1}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

 and ..., and will also take on a value between 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}+dy_{n}$
\end_inset

 at a later time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
The conditional probabilities can be obtained from the absolute ones by
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
P_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n}|y_{n-1},t_{n-1};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right) & = & \frac{p_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right)}{p_{n-1}\left(y_{n-1},t_{n-1};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right)}.\label{eq:conditional RP in terms of absolute}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The above follows from the definition of probabilities: to see that, rewrite
 it in the form:
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right) & = & P_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n}|y_{n-1},t_{n-1};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right)p_{n-1}\left(y_{n-1},t_{n-1};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right).\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

By definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the probability that we obtain a value between 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}+dy_{n}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

 given that we obtained a value between 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n-1}+dy_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 and ...
 and that we obtained a value between 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}+dy_{1}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}.$
\end_inset

 And by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "def:prob random process"

\end_inset

,
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset

 tells us the probability that the random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 will take on a value between 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}+dy_{1}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

 and ..., and will also take on a value between 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n-1}+dy_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 at a later time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 (and this probability is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n-1}$
\end_inset

)
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 AND that given all of the previous, a value between 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}+dy_{n}$
\end_inset

 is obtained at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

 (and this probability is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n}$
\end_inset

).
 Hence, the equality is derived.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Also, the above equality means that 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n}$
\end_inset

 is properly normalized to 1: Consider 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\int dy_{n}P_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n}|y_{n-1},t_{n-1};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right) & = & \int dy_{n}\frac{p_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right)}{p_{n-1}\left(y_{n-1},t_{n-1};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right)}.\\
 & = & \frac{\int dy_{n}p_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right)}{p_{n-1}\left(y_{n-1},t_{n-1};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right)}\\
 & = & \frac{p_{n-1}\left(y_{n-1},t_{n-1};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right)}{p_{n-1}\left(y_{n-1},t_{n-1};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right)}\\
 & = & 1,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where the before last equality comes from the definition of probabilities.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Eq.
 6.5 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "blandfordCP"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Notation used by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "blandfordCP"

\end_inset

 to describe stationary processes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Denote
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{1}\left(y\right) & \equiv & p_{1}\left(y,t_{1}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

since it does not depend on the time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Denote
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{2}\left(y_{2},t|y_{2}\right) & \equiv & P_{2}\left(y_{2},t|y_{1},0\right)\\
 & \equiv & P_{2}\left(y_{2},t|y_{1}\right),
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

for the probability that, if a (realization of a) random process begins
 with the value 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

, then after the lapse of a time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 it has the value 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The ergodic Hypothesis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Preview

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}[Ergodic Hypothesis for Random Processes]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:ergodic hypothesis"

\end_inset

A (stationary) random process is said to be 
\emph on
ergodic
\emph default
 (or to satisfy the ergodic hypothesis) IFF it satisfies the following property:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $y\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 be any realization of the process (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "def:realization"

\end_inset

).
 Construct from 
\begin_inset Formula $y\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 a new ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{E}^{'}$
\end_inset

 whose members are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Y^{K}\left(t\right)\equiv y\left(t+KT\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $K\in\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $T\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 .
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(Y_{n},t_{n};\cdots;Y_{1},t_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 has the same functional form as 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n};\,\cdots;\, y_{1},t_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 for all times such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|t_{i}-t_{j}\right|<T$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Under this assumption, time averages for function 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 defined using a realization (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "def:realization"

\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula $y\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is the same as the ensemble average:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\bar{F} & = & \lim_{T\rightarrow\infty}\frac{1}{T}\int_{-T/2}^{T/2}F\left(y\left(t\right)\right)dt\quad\mbox{(Time average)}\nonumber \\
 & = & \left\langle F\left(y\right)\right\rangle =\int F\left(y\right)p_{1}\left(y\right)dy,\label{eq:implication ergodicity}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 is defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "def:prob random process"

\end_inset

 [[TYPO: ^
\begin_inset Note Comment
status collapsed

