\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "def:ergodic hypothesis"

\end_inset

is not very clear and its implications are stated but not derived.
 Ergodicity and its meaning is a difficult subject.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "OliveiraET"

\end_inset

 discusses ergodic theory in the context of classical statistical mechanics.
 The article is not very well written and requires some level of mathematical
 background but is well organized and one can extract some ideas from it:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The definition of ergodicity is specified (in different ways) to be: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

An invariant measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 with respect to a general dynamics 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{t}$
\end_inset

 is called ergodic (or the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\tau^{t},\mu\right)$
\end_inset

 is ergodic) if for every set 
\begin_inset Formula $A\subset\Omega$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{t}\left(A\right)=A$
\end_inset

, one has either 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(A\right)=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\Omega\backslash A\right)=0$
\end_inset

, i.e., every invariant set under the dynamics has zero or full measure.
 Then ergodicity means that the only nontrivial (that is, with nonzero measure)
 invariant set is just the whole set; in other words, ergodicity is equivalent
 to the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 be 
\emph on
indecomposable
\emph default
 under the dynamics 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\tau^{t},\mu\right)$
\end_inset

.
 If it is clear what is the invariant measure under consideration, one also
 says that the system or the dynamics 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{t}$
\end_inset

 is ergodic.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 is a set and invariant measure means that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mu\left(\tau^{t}\left(A\right)\right)=\mu\left(A\right),$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\forall t$
\end_inset

, for all suitable 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

...
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

If for each integrable 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 the time average 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 is constant 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

−
\emph on
a.e.
\emph default
, then the pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\tau^{t},\mu\right)$
\end_inset

 is called ergodic.
 Note that this implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
f^{*}\left(\omega\right) & = & \int_{\Omega}f\left(\omega^{'}\right)d\mu\left(\omega^{'}\right),\quad\mu-a.e.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

that is, the equality of space and time averages.
 If the flow 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{t}$
\end_inset

 is fixed, it is also common to say that the invariant measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is ergodic.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Note that the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $f^{*}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
f^{*}\left(\xi\right) & \equiv & \lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\frac{1}{t}\int_{t_{0}}^{t_{0}+t}f\left(T^{s}\xi\right)ds,\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}$
\end_inset

 is some initial time 
\begin_inset Formula $ $
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{s}\xi$
\end_inset

 indicates time evolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi$
\end_inset

 by time 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, 
\emph on
a.e.

\emph default
 refers to: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

(this means “almost everywhere,” a short way of saying “except on a set
 of zero measure”)
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Ergodicity in the context of statistical mechanics is explained: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\series bold
Ergodic hypothesis in statistical mechanics
\series default
: The microcanonical ensemble 
\begin_inset Formula $d\xi$
\end_inset

 is ergodic with respect to the Hamiltonian dynamics.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 In the context of classical statistical mechanics, 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=\left(q,p\right)$
\end_inset

 is a collection of the positions 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 and momenta 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 of the constituent particles of the system.
 
\begin_inset Formula $d\xi$
\end_inset

 is the measure of the system.
 For instance, the phase space average of an observable 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\left\langle f\right\rangle  & \equiv & \int_{\Gamma}f\left(\xi\right)\rho_{t}\left(\xi\right)d\xi,\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Gamma$
\end_inset

 is the phase space of the system and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the density function at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Nonergodicity is quite common and sometimes could mean the coexistence of
 two phases (see section 4.1).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Mixing entails ergodicity but the converse does not necessarily hold (section
 4.1).
 The intuitive definition of mixing is for example stirring a drop of ink
 in a liquid.
 A precise definition was given by Von Neumann: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\left(\tau^{t},\mu\right)$
\end_inset

 is mixing (
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is assumed to be invariant) if for any 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B\subset\Omega$
\end_inset

 one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\mu\left(\tau^{t}\left(A\right)\cap B\right) & = & \mu\left(A\right)\mu\left(B\right)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This expression means that as time increases the portion of a given measurable
 set 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 that then resides in any set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is proportional to the measure of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

; thus, according to the probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{t}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 becomes uniformly distributed over 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset


\series default
.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
To see why, note that if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is uniformly distributed then for any set 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 the probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $A\cap B$
\end_inset

 is simply the measure/probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 multiplied by the measure/probability of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Section 5 says that we might be able to justify the microcanonical ensemble
 without passing through the ergodicity hypothesis: by taking the limit
 of infinitely many particles and showing that all the resultant thermodynamics
 are equivalent.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

An invariant measure is said to result in a thermodynamics if the Boltzmann
 
\emph on
heat theorem 
\emph default
holds
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The heat theorem holds if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{1}{T}\left(du+pdv\right),\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

[where 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 is the intensive internal energy, 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 the pressure and 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 the intensive volume] is an exact differential 
\begin_inset Formula $ds$
\end_inset

, which allows the introduction of the entropy 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 as a function of state 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(u,v\right)$
\end_inset

, a fundamental ingredient.
 Note that this is an analytic expression for the second law of thermodynamics.
 As a matter of fact, the proper way of taking the thermodynamic limit depends
 on the ensemble considered, and in some cases different ensembles may correspon
d to different physical situations; for example, ﬁxed external boundary
 conditions can generate new ensembles.
 Now by restricting to these distributions, and also for the systems one
 also proves that in the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $V,N\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 the same entropy function 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 results (as well as the same thermodynamic potentials), then the same thermodyn
amics is generated without ambiguity.
 The ergodic question would be avoided, while the number of particles is
 asked to be very large.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Also, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

we underline that for a large class of particle interactions..., the standard
 microcanonical, canonical and grand canonical distributions generate the
 same thermodynamics; however, it is worth mentioning that the important
 cases of Coulomb and gravitational potentials are not included in such
 proofs.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (I don't quite understand this argument).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Markov Random Processes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Preview

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}[Markov Random Process]
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "def:Markov Process"

\end_inset

A random process 
\begin_inset Formula $y\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is said to be Markov/
\emph on
Markovian
\emph default
 IFF
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n}|y_{n-1},t_{n-1};\cdots;y_{1},t_{1}\right) & = & P_{2}\left(y_{n},t_{n}|y_{n-1},t_{n-1}\right)\quad\mbox{for all }t_{n}\geq\cdots\geq t_{2}\geq t_{1},\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}$
\end_inset

 are conditional probabilities defined from the probability distribution
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "def:prob random process"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From this definition, and the definitions of stationarity and ergodicity
 we have the the following :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:ErgodicP2"

\end_inset

An ergodic process satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}P_{2}\left(y_{2},t|y_{1}\right) & = & p_{1}\left(y_{2}\right)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In section 2.2.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NewmanMC"

\end_inset

, it is stated that the condition ergodicity means that it should be possible
 for a Markov process to reach any state of the system from any other state
 if we wait long enough.
 This is implied in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:implication ergodicity"

\end_inset

, where the ensemble average is equal to the time average because a realization
 
\begin_inset Formula $y\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 gets to explore all possible values of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 passes through all states of the phase space with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This + markotivity means that some kind of equilibrium will be reached:
 we will have to return to the initial state eventually where because the
 process is Markovian, the process repeats itself.
 So in this sense, what the initial state of the process does not matter
 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}P_{2}\left(y_{2},t|y_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Moreover, we know that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{2}\left(y_{2},t|y_{1}\right) & = & \frac{p_{2}\left(y_{2},t;y_{1}\right)}{p\left(y_{1}\right)}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

If the RHS is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}\left(y_{2},t;y_{1}\right)\propto p\left(y_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, as we argued previously 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 becomes independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 and time at 
\begin_inset Formula $t\rightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}\left(y_{2},t;y_{1}\right)=p_{1}\left(y_{2}\right)p_{1}\left(y_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 an 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}P_{2}\left(y_{2},t|y_{1}\right) & = & p_{1}\left(y_{2}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From that Lemma, we can write that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Preview

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm: P2 is king"

\end_inset

For any Markovian, stationary and ergodic process, all the probability distribut
ions follow from 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}\left(y_{2},t|y_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 alone.*
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
From the definition of a Markovian process (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "def:Markov Process"

\end_inset

), all conditional probabilities can be obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}\left(y_{n},t_{n}|y_{n-1},t_{n-1}\right)$
\end_inset

 which for a stationary process can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}\left(y_{n},t_{n}-t_{n-1}|y_{n-1},0\right)=P_{2}\left(y_{n},t|y_{n-1},0\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
From Bayes rule, we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n};\cdots;y_{1},t_{1}\right) & = & P_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n}|y_{n-1},t_{n-1};\cdots;y_{1},t_{1}\right)p_{n-1}\left(y_{n-1},t_{n-1};\cdots;y_{1},t_{n-1}\right)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Consider a stationary Markovian process then this becomes
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n};\cdots;y_{1}\right) & = & P_{2}\left(y_{n},t_{n}|y_{n-1},t_{n-1}\right)p_{n-1}\left(y_{n-1},t_{n-1};\cdots;y_{1}\right)\\
 & = & P_{2}\left(y_{n},t|y_{n-1},t_{n-1}\right)P_{n-1}\left(y_{n-1},t_{n-1}|...\right)p_{n-1}\left(y_{n-1},...\right)\\
 & = & P_{2}\left(y_{n},t_{n}-t_{n-1}|y_{n-1},0\right)P_{2}\left(y_{n-1},t_{n-1}-t_{n-2}|y_{n-2}\right)p_{n-1}\\
 &  & \vdots\\
 & = & \prod_{i=0}^{n-2}P_{2}\left(y_{n-i},t_{n-i}-t_{n-i-1}|y_{n-i-1}\right)p_{1}\left(y_{1}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

So for a general distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset

 all we need to know are 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}\left(y_{n},t|y_{n-1}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\left(y_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Further note that all 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}\left(y_{n},t|y_{n-1}\right)$
\end_inset

 are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}\left(y_{2},t|y_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Now, for 
\emph on
ergodic processes
\emph default
: Use 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "lem:ErgodicP2"

\end_inset

 to write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}P_{2}\left(y_{2},t|y_{1}\right) & = & p_{1}\left(y_{2}\right).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 Hence, we can obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}$
\end_inset

 and all we need to know is 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(Unsuccessful attempt at proof: 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\emph on
Unsuccessful
\emph default
 attempt at the proof:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\bar{F} & = & \lim_{T\rightarrow\infty}\frac{1}{T}\int_{-T/2}^{T/2}\left[\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}P_{2}\left(y_{2},t|y\left(s\right)\right)\right]ds\\
 & = & \lim_{T\rightarrow\infty}\frac{1}{T}\int_{-T/2}^{T/2}\left[\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\frac{p_{2}\left(y_{2},t;y\left(s\right)\right)}{p_{1}\left(y\left(s\right)\right)}\right]ds\\
 & = & \left\langle F\left(y\right)\right\rangle =\int\left[\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}P_{2}\left(y_{2},t|y\right)\right]p_{1}\left(y\right)dy,\\
 & = & \int\left[\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\frac{p_{2}\left(y_{2},t;y\right)}{p_{1}\left(y\right)}\right]p_{1}\left(y\right)dy\\
 & = & \int\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}p_{2}\left(y_{2},t;y\right)dy,
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 Also, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\bar{F} & = & \lim_{T\rightarrow\infty}\frac{1}{T}\int_{y\left(-T/2\right)}^{y\left(T/2\right)}\left[\lim_{t\rightarrow\infty}\frac{p_{2}\left(y_{2},t;y\left(s\right)\right)}{p_{1}\left(y\left(s\right)\right)}\right]ds\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Another 
\emph on
unsuccessful
\emph default
 attempt:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This argument is inspired from Sec.
 2.2.3 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NewmanMC"

\end_inset

 on detailed balance.
 From that section, if detailed balance is satisfied, i.e.
 if
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{\mu}P\left(\mu\rightarrow\nu\right) & = & p_{\nu}P\left(\nu\rightarrow\mu\right),\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\mu}$
\end_inset

 is the equilibrium probability to be in state 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 (equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

) and 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\mu\rightarrow\nu\right)$
\end_inset

 is the transition probability from state 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 (and is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{2}\left(y_{2},t|y_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

), then simple equilibrium is reached.
 There is no reason for this 
\end_layout

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
