\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{example}[Markov Processes]
\end_layout

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

An example of Markov process is the 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

-component of velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{x}(t)$
\end_inset

 of a dust particle in an arbitrarily large room ﬁlled with constant-temperature
 air.
 Why? Because the molecule’s equation of motion is 
\begin_inset Formula $mdv_{x}/dt=F_{x}^{'}(t),$
\end_inset

 and the force 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{x}^{'}(t)$
\end_inset

 is due to random buffeting by other molecules that are uncorrelated (the
 kick now is unrelated to earlier kicks); thus, there is no way for the
 value of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{x}$
\end_inset

 in the future to be inﬂuenced by any earlier values of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{x}$
\end_inset

 except the most recent one.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (Section 6.3.1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "blandfordCP"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

By contrast, the position 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 of the particle is not Markov because the probabilities of future values
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 depend not just on the initial value of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, but also on the initial velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{x}$
\end_inset

—or, equivalently, the probabilities depend on the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 at two initial, closely spaced times[[*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I am not sure what 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "blandfordCP"

\end_inset

 is talking about but looking at the EOM 
\begin_inset Formula $mdv_{x}/dt=F_{x}^{'}(t),$
\end_inset

 we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
m\ddot{x} & = & F_{x}^{'}\\
\implies\dot{x} & = & \int\frac{F_{x}^{'}}{m}dt+v_{x}\left(t_{0}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{F_{x}\left(t\right)}{m}+v_{x}\left(t_{0}\right)\\
\implies x & = & \int\frac{F_{x}\left(t\right)}{m}dt+v_{x}\left(t_{0}\right)t+x\left(t_{0}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 does depend on the entire previous history and not just on the most recent
 time.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

]].
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x\left(t\right),v_{x}\left(t\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

 is a two-dimensional Markov process[[*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The equations of motion for the system are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{d}{dt}\left(\begin{array}{c}
x\\
v_{x}
\end{array}\right) & = & \left(\begin{array}{c}
v_{x}\\
F_{x}^{'}/m
\end{array}\right)\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 which looks like a Markov EOM ?? 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

]].
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (Section 6.3.1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "blandfordCP"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

