\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{thm}[The Smoluchowski Equation]
\end_layout

\end_inset

For any Markovian, stationary process and for times 
\begin_inset Formula $0<t_{2}<t_{3}$
\end_inset

, we can write that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{2}\left(y_{3},t_{3}|y_{1}\right) & = & \int P_{2}\left(y_{3},t_{3}-t_{2}|y_{2}\right)P_{2}\left(y_{2},t_{2}-t_{1}|y_{1}\right)dy_{2}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{2}\left(y_{3},t_{3}|y_{1},t_{1}\right) & = & \int P_{3}\left(y_{3},t_{3}|y_{2},t_{2};y_{1},t_{1}\right)P_{2}\left(y_{2},t_{2}|y_{1},t_{1}\right)dy_{2}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}<t_{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}>t_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The above statement is true because of conservation of probability and
 because the realization 
\begin_inset Formula $y\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 has to have a certain value at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Afterward, use the fact that the process is Markovian to write that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{2}\left(y_{3},t_{3}|y_{1},t_{1}\right) & = & \int P_{2}\left(y_{3},t_{3}|y_{2},t_{2}\right)P_{2}\left(y_{2},t_{2}|y_{1},t_{1}\right)dy_{2}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Use the fact that the process is stationary to obtain that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P_{2}\left(y_{3},t_{3}|y_{1},t_{1}\right) & = & \int P_{2}\left(y_{3},t_{3}-t_{2}|y_{2}\right)P_{2}\left(y_{2},t_{2}-t_{1}|y_{1}\right)dy_{2}\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Gaussian Random Processes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Preview

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{defn}[Gaussian (Stationary) Random Process]
\end_layout

\end_inset

A random process is said to be Gaussian IFF all its probability distributions
 are Gaussian:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
p_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right) & = & A\exp\left[-\sum_{j=1}^{n}\sum_{k=1}^{n}\alpha_{jk}\left(y_{j}-\bar{y}\right)\left(y_{k}-\bar{y}\right)\right],\label{eq:gaussian random process}\\
\nonumber 
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset

 is defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "def:prob random process"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A>0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\alpha_{jk}\right]$
\end_inset

 is a positive-definite matrix*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Otherwise 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset

 would not be normalizable.
 Indeed
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right) & = & A\exp\left[-\vec{Y}^{T}\overleftrightarrow{\alpha}\vec{Y}\right],\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{Y}$
\end_inset

 is the vertical vector corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[y_{j}-\bar{y}\right]$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Claim: 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset

 is normalizable IFF 
\begin_inset Formula $\overleftrightarrow{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is positive definite.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\implies\right)$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\overleftrightarrow{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is positive definite then by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{Y}^{T}\overleftrightarrow{\alpha}\vec{Y}$
\end_inset

 is positive and so 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}$
\end_inset

 is decaying exponential and so normalizable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Longleftarrow\right)$
\end_inset

We want 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{Y}^{T}\overleftrightarrow{\alpha}\vec{Y}$
\end_inset

 to be positive for all possible 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{Y}$
\end_inset

 then by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $\overleftrightarrow{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 is positive definite.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The process is also time-stationary (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "def: Stationary Random Process"

\end_inset

), if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{jk}$
\end_inset

 depend only on the time differences such as 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}-t_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{3}-t_{1}$
\end_inset

, etc ...
 Further, 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{y}$
\end_inset

 is a constant that is equal to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\bar{y} & = & \left\langle y\right\rangle =\int yp_{1}\left(y\right)dy\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

 is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
p_{1}\left(y_{1}\right) & = & A\exp\left[-\alpha\left(y_{1}-\bar{y}\right)^{2}\right].\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}yp_{1}\left(y\right)dy$
\end_inset

 with Mathematica gives the desired answer.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{defn}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Properties of Gaussian Processes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Preview

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{thm}
\end_layout

\end_inset

The conditional probabilities of a Gaussian process (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:gaussian random process"

\end_inset

) will be Gaussians themselves (i.e.
 of the form of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:gaussian random process"

\end_inset

)*
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
From 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "eq:conditional RP in terms of absolute"

\end_inset

, we can write that (letting 
\begin_inset Formula $P\equiv P_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n}|y_{n-1},t_{n-1};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

)
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P & = & \frac{p_{n}\left(y_{n},t_{n};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right)}{p_{n-1}\left(y_{n-1},t_{n-1};\cdots;y_{2},t_{2};y_{1};t_{1}\right)}\\
 & = & \frac{A\exp\left[-\sum_{j=1}^{n}\sum_{k=1}^{n}\alpha_{jk}\left(y_{j}-\bar{y}\right)\left(y_{k}-\bar{y}\right)\right]}{B\exp\left[-\sum_{j=1}^{n-1}\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}\beta_{jk}\left(y_{j}-\bar{y}\right)\left(y_{k}-\bar{y}\right)\right]}\\
 & = & \frac{A\exp\left[-\vec{Y}^{T}\overleftrightarrow{\alpha}\vec{Y}\right]}{B\exp\left[-\vec{Y}_{n}^{T}\overleftrightarrow{\gamma}\vec{Y}_{n}\right]},\\
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\overleftrightarrow{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\overleftrightarrow{\beta}$
\end_inset

 appended with 0s: 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{nl}=\gamma_{ln}=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $l=1,\cdots,n$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\overleftrightarrow{\gamma} & = & \left(\begin{array}{cc}
\overleftrightarrow{\beta} & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right)\\
\vec{Y} & = & \left(\begin{array}{c}
y_{1}\\
\vdots\\
y_{n}
\end{array}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

so that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{Y}^{T}\overleftrightarrow{\gamma}\vec{Y} & = & \left(\begin{array}{ccc}
y_{1} & \cdots & y_{n}\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\overleftrightarrow{\beta} & 0\\
0 & 0
\end{array}\right)\left(\begin{array}{c}
y_{1}\\
\vdots\\
y_{n}
\end{array}\right)\\
 & = & \vec{Y}_{n-1}^{T}\overleftrightarrow{\beta}\vec{Y}_{n-1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

because 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{n}$
\end_inset

 can be anything and would not change the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{Y}^{T}\overleftrightarrow{\gamma}\vec{Y}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
P & = & \frac{A}{B}\exp\left(-\vec{Y}^{T}\left(\overleftrightarrow{\alpha}-\overleftrightarrow{\gamma}\right)\vec{Y}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Is 
\begin_inset Formula $\overleftrightarrow{\alpha}-\overleftrightarrow{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 positive? (unsuccessful attempt: 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

